                    id: "lesson-2-1",
                    title: "The Raw Approach: React via CDN",
                    content: "# The Raw Approach: React via CDN\n\nTo prove that React is just a library, we can inject it directly into a standard HTML file without installing any software.\n1. Create an index.html file and an empty script.js file.\n2. In your HTML <body>, create an empty <div> with an id=\"root\". This will be the container where React injects our entire application.\n3. Go to the official React documentation and copy the CDN (Content Delivery Network) links for two specific libraries:\n   * React: The core library that builds UI components.\n   * React DOM: The bridge library that connects React's UI components to the browser's actual DOM.\n```html\n<body>\n    <div id=\"root\"></div>\n\n\n    <script crossorigin src=\"https://unpkg.com/react@18/umd/react.development.js\"></script>\n    <script crossorigin src=\"https://unpkg.com/react-dom@18/umd/react-dom.development.js\"></script>\n    \n    <script src=\"script.js\"></script>\n</body>\n\n```\n\n\nCreating an Element the \"React\" Way: Inside script.js, instead of using Vanilla JS (document.createElement), we ask React to do it:\n```javascript\n// 1. Create an h1 element using React\nconst myHeading = React.createElement(\"h1\", null, \"Hello from React!\");\n\n\n// 2. Select our empty div container\nconst parentDiv = document.querySelector(\"#root\");\n\n\n// 3. Create a React Root\nconst root = ReactDOM.createRoot(parentDiv);\n\n\n// 4. Render the heading inside the root\nroot.render(myHeading);\n\n```\n\n\nWhen you open this in the browser, you will see \"Hello from React!\". Notice the division of labor: React created the element in memory, and ReactDOM was responsible for physically rendering it onto the browser screen."
